explanation:
The TCP/IP Network layer defines the end-to-end routing of data. Also, the term packet (as mentioned in the question) defines the data that the network layer forwards from sending host to destination host.

	For the incorrect answers:

	The TCP/IP Application layer provides application software with an interface to the network in ways that simplify the interface so that the application can ask the network to deliver data to some destination address.

	The TCP/IP Transport layer deals with error recovery, segmentation of large application data blocks for transport, and the reassembly of segmented application data.

	The TCP/IP data link layer defines how to deliver data over a particular instance of a particular type of data link, for instance, over a single Ethernet LAN, serial WAN, or Ethernet WAN link. However, it does not define end-to-end routing of data.&nbsp;

	&nbsp;

When a router processes an incoming packet, the router de-encapsulates the packet from the data link frame and then re-encapsulates the packet in a new data link frame before forwarding the new frame. The reason is the changing data link layer addresses and/or interface technologies (Ethernet versus HDLC).&nbsp;

	In this case, the question asks how many times the packet will be encapsulated. Note that the packet begins within R1, not from a host outside R1. So, the IP packet will first be encapsulated on R1. From here, it will be sent to R2, which will de-encapsulate the packet from the Ethernet frame and re-encapsulate the IP packet into another Ethernet frame. From here, R3 will de-encapsulate the packet from the Ethernet frame and re-encapsulate the IP packet into an HDLC frame. From here, R4 will de-encapsulate the packet from the HDLC frame and re-encapsulate the IP packet into an Ethernet frame. From there, the frame holding that packet will arrive at R5, which will de-encapsulate the packet from the Ethernet frame and process it. However, R5 will not encapsulate the packet for forwarding again, as R5 is the destination.

	&nbsp;

	So to add them up: R1 (encapsulate), R2 (de-encapsulate/re-encapsulate), R3 (de-encapsulate/re-encapsulate), R4 (de-encapsulate/re-encapsulate) = 4.

&nbsp;

	By default, a router will compare the destination IP address in the packet with its routing table to determine the outgoing interface and possibly the next-hop router IP address.

	For the incorrect answers, the router will use the FCS (in the data link header) for its usual function of determining if the frame contained any errors before the router allows itself to continue with the packet forwarding process. The router does not check the layer 3 source IP address or the layer 2 destination MAC address when making its forwarding decision.

The networksetup -getinfo Ethernet command is used to show the configured default gateway on a macOS device.&nbsp;

To find out the configured IP address, mask, default gateway, and DNS servers on a Windows machine, you would need to leverage ipconfig /all, because the ipconfig command does not show the configured DNS servers. If you only needed to verify the IP address, mask, and default gateway, you could have leveraged ipconfig.

The netstat -rn command shows&nbsp;the local routing table on a Windows, macOS, and Linux device.
